Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1 & 2. Guard Navigation with a Confirmation Dialog

In your `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges
        && args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it you'd have a race condition.
- **`args.Cancel()`** prevents the back navigation.
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` to only intercept back navigation.

## 3. Custom "Cancel" Back Button

In your `EditProductPage.xaml`, attach `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `Command` lets you handle the tap yourself (e.g., show the same confirmation or just navigate back):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

> **Note:** When using `BackButtonBehavior.Command`, the command replaces the default back action entirely — you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself to actually navigate back. The `OnNavigating` guard still fires if you use `GoToAsync`, so you can choose one approach or both (belt-and-suspenders). If using both, have the guard check a flag to avoid a double-prompt.
